# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: zero-shot-learning
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It can also be defined as the practice of designing and refining input instructions given to a generative AI model to produce more accurate, relevant, or useful outputs.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Effective prompt engineering involves understanding how a model interprets language, and may include techniques such as few-shot prompting, chain-of-thought prompting, and role assignment.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It is increasingly considered a skill for working with large language models (LLMs) in both research and professional contexts.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] During the 2020s AI boom, prompt engineering became regarded as a business capability across corporations and industries.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Employees with the title **prompt engineer** were hired to create prompts that would increase productivity and efficacy, although the individual title has since lost traction amid AI models that produce better prompts than humans and corporate training in prompting for general employees.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Common prompting techniques include multi-shot, chain-of-thought, and tree-of-thought prompting, as well as assigning roles to the model.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Automated prompt generation methods, such as retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), provide for greater accuracy and a wider scope of functions for prompt engineers.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt injection is a type of cybersecurity attack that targets machine learning models through malicious prompts.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt is some natural language text that describes and prescribes the task that an artificial intelligence (AI) should perform.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt for a text-to-text language model can be a query, a command, or a longer statement referencing context, instructions, and conversation history.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The process of prompt engineering may involve designing clear queries, refining wording, providing relevant context, specifying the style of output, and assigning a character for the AI to mimic in order to guide the model toward more accurate, useful, and consistent responses.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] When communicating with a text-to-image or a text-to-audio model, a typical prompt contains a description of a desired output such as "a high-quality photo of an astronaut riding a horse" or "Lo-fi slow BPM electro chill with organic samples".
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt engineering may be applied to text-to-image models to achieve a desired subject, style, layout, lighting, and aesthetic.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Common terms used to describe various specific prompt engineering techniques include *chain-of-thought*, *tree-of-thought*, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A 2024 survey of the field identified over 50 distinct text-based prompting techniques, 40 multimodal variants, and a vocabulary of 33 terms used across prompting research, highlighting a present lack of standardised terminology for prompt engineering.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Vibe coding is an AI-assisted software development method where a user prompts an LLM with a description of what they want and lets it generate or edit the code.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2025, "vibe coding" was the Collins Dictionary word of the year.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Context engineering is a related process that focuses on the context elements that accompany user prompts, which include system instructions, retrieved knowledge, tool definitions, conversation summaries, and task metadata.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Context engineering is performed to improve reliability, provenance and token efficiency in production LLM systems.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The concept emphasises operational practices such as token budgeting, provenance tags, versioning of context artifacts, observability (logging which context was supplied), and context regression tests to ensure that changes to supplied context do not silently alter system behaviour.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Research has found that the performance of large language models (LLMs) is highly sensitive to choices such as the ordering of examples, the quality of demonstration labels, and even small variations in phrasing.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In some cases, reordering examples in a prompt produced accuracy shifts of more than 40 percent.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A model's ability to temporarily learn from prompts is known as *in-context learning*.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In-context learning is an emergent ability of large language models.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It is an emergent property of model scale, meaning that breaks in scaling laws occur, leading to its efficacy increasing at a different rate in larger models than in smaller models.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Unlike training and fine-tuning, which produce lasting changes, in-context learning is temporary.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Training models to perform in-context learning can be viewed as a form of meta-learning, or "learning to learn".
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Research consistently demonstrates that LLMs are highly sensitive to subtle variations in prompt formatting, structure, and linguistic properties.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Some studies have shown up to 76 accuracy points across formatting changes in few-shot settings.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Linguistic features significantly influence prompt effectiveness—such as morphology, syntax, and lexico-semantic changes—which meaningfully enhance task performance across a variety of tasks.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Clausal syntax, for example, improves consistency and reduces uncertainty in knowledge retrieval.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This sensitivity persists even with larger model sizes, additional few-shot examples, or instruction tuning.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] To address sensitivity of models and make them more robust, several evaluative methods have been proposed.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] FormatSpread facilitates systematic analysis by evaluating a range of plausible prompt formats, offering a more comprehensive performance interval.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Similarly, PromptEval estimates performance distributions across diverse prompts, enabling robust metrics such as performance quantiles and accurate evaluations under constrained budgets.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A prompt may include a few examples for a model to learn from in-context, an implementation of few-shot learning for LLMs.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It is possible to fine-tune models on CoT reasoning datasets to enhance this capability further and stimulate better interpretability.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] As originally proposed by Google, each CoT prompt is accompanied by a set of input/output examples—called *exemplars*—to demonstrate the desired model output, making it a few-shot prompting technique.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] However, according to a later paper from researchers at Google and the University of Tokyo, simply appending the words "Let's think step-by-step" was also effective, which allowed for CoT to be employed as a zero-shot technique.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2022, text-to-image models like DALL-E 2, Stable Diffusion, and Midjourney were released to the public.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] These models take text prompts as input and use them to generate images.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Early text-to-image models typically do not understand negation, grammar and sentence structure in the same way as large language models, and may thus require a different set of prompting techniques.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The prompt "a party with no cake" may produce an image including a cake.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A text-to-image prompt commonly includes a description of the subject of the art, the desired medium (such as *digital painting* or *photography*), style (such as *hyperrealistic* or *pop-art*), lighting (such as *rim lighting* or *crepuscular rays*), color, and texture.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Word order also affects the output of a text-to-image prompt.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Words closer to the start of a prompt may be emphasized more heavily.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Some text-to-image models are capable of imitating the style of particular artists by name.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] For example, the phrase *in the style of Greg Rutkowski* has been used in Stable Diffusion and Midjourney prompts to generate images in the distinctive style of Polish digital artist Greg Rutkowski.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Famous artists such as Vincent van Gogh and Salvador Dalí have also been used for styling and testing.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] For text-to-image models, *textual inversion* performs an optimization process to create a new word embedding based on a set of example images.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This embedding vector acts as a "pseudo-word" which can be included in a prompt to express the content or style of the examples.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2023, Meta's AI research released Segment Anything, a computer vision model that can perform image segmentation by prompting.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] As an alternative to text prompts, Segment Anything can accept bounding boxes, segmentation masks, and foreground/background points.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The process of writing and refining a prompt for an LLM or generative AI shares some parallels with an iterative engineering design process, such as by discovering reusable best practices through reproducible experimentation.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] However, several fundamental limitations constrain its reliability as a discipline.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Effective prompting strategies are highly model specific, a technique that improves performance on one model may degrade it on another, making generalization difficult.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Prompts are also brittle: minor surface-level changes in phrasing, punctuation, or word order can produce dramatically different outputs, even when the semantic intent remains identical.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This instability makes it difficult to establish durable, transferable prompt patterns across deployment contexts.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Furthermore, as AI models continue to improve in their ability to interpret user intent directly, many manual prompting techniques are becoming obsolete.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Advances in instruction-following and model reasoning have reduced the marginal value of elaborate prompt construction for everyday tasks, raising questions about the long-term viability of prompt engineering as a standalone discipline.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Recent research has explored automated prompt engineering, using optimization algorithms to generate or refine prompts without human intervention.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] These automated approaches aim to identify effective prompt patterns by analyzing model gradients, reinforcement feedback, or evolutionary processes, reducing the need for manual experimentation.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Retrieval-augmented generation is a technique that enables GenAI models to retrieve and incorporate new information.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It modifies interactions with an LLM so that the model responds to user queries with reference to a specified set of documents, using this information to supplement information from its pre-existing training data.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This allows LLMs to use domain-specific and/or updated information.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] RAG improves large language models by incorporating information retrieval before generating responses.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Unlike traditional LLMs that rely on static training data, RAG pulls relevant text from databases, uploaded documents, or web sources.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] By dynamically retrieving information, RAG enables AI to generate more accurate responses and fewer AI hallucinations without frequent retraining.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] GraphRAG (coined by Microsoft Research) is a technique that extends RAG with the use of a knowledge graph to allow the model to connect disparate pieces of information, synthesize insights, and understand summarized semantic concepts over large data collections.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] It was shown to be effective on datasets like the Violent Incident Information from News Articles.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] LLMs themselves can be used to compose prompts for LLMs.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] CoT examples can be generated by LLM themselves.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In "auto-CoT", a library of questions are converted to vectors by a model such as BERT.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Questions close to the centroid of each cluster are selected, in order to have a subset of diverse questions.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] An LLM does zero-shot CoT on each selected question.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The question and the corresponding CoT answer are added to a dataset of demonstrations.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] These diverse demonstrations can then added to prompts for few-shot learning.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In "prefix-tuning", "prompt tuning", or "soft prompting", floating-point vectors are searched directly by gradient descent to maximize the log-likelihood on outputs.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] An earlier result uses the same idea of gradient descent search, but is designed for masked language models like BERT, and searches only over token sequences, rather than numerical vectors.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Formally, it searches for $\arg \max _{\tilde {X}}\sum _{i}\log Pr[Y^{i}|{\tilde {X}}\ast X^{i}]$ where ${\tilde {X}}$ ranges over token sequences of a specified length.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Early precedents of structured user interaction with ruled-based AI systems can be found in enterprise automation software from 1990s.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] For example, The Intelligent Filling Manager (1999), developed by Krishna C.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Mukherjee, used a dynamic Q&A interface driven by rule-based expert system to collect user inputs for generating regulatory filings automatically across jurisdictions.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] While not involving neural networks, such systems featured prompt-like workflows that influenced later human-in-the-loop AI designs.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2018, researchers first proposed that all previously separate tasks in natural language processing (NLP) could be cast as question-answer problems over a context.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The AI boom saw an increased focus within academic literature and professional practice on applying prompting techniques to get the model to output the desired outcome and avoid nonsensical output, a process characterized by trial-and-error.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] According to *The Wall Street Journal* in 2025, the job of prompt engineer was one of the hottest in 2023, but has become obsolete due to models that better intuit user intent and to company trainings.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] A repository for prompts reported that over 2,000 public prompts for around 170 datasets were available in February 2022.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2022, the *chain-of-thought* prompting technique was proposed by Google researchers.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] In 2023, several text-to-text and text-to-image prompt databases were made publicly available.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] The Personalized Image-Prompt (PIP) dataset, a generated image-text dataset that has been categorized by 3,115 users, has also been made available publicly in 2024.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] Prompt injection is a cybersecurity exploit in which adversaries craft inputs that appear legitimate but are designed to cause unintended behavior in machine learning models, particularly large language models.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] This attack takes advantage of the model's inability to distinguish between developer-defined prompts and user inputs, allowing adversaries to bypass safeguards and influence model behaviour.
[src:zero-shot-learning/in-context-learning] While LLMs are designed to follow trusted instructions, they can be manipulated into carrying out unintended responses through carefully crafted inputs.
[src:zero-shot-learning/semantic-search] Some authors regard semantic search as a set of techniques for retrieving knowledge from richly structured data sources like ontologies and XML as found on the Semantic Web.
[src:zero-shot-learning/semantic-search] Such technologies enable the formal articulation of domain knowledge at a high level of expressiveness and could enable the user to specify their intent in more detail at query time.
[src:zero-shot-learning/semantic-search] The articulation enhances content relevance and depth by including specific places, people, or concepts relevant to the query.
[src:zero-shot-learning/semantic-search] Tools like Google's Knowledge Graph provide structured relationships between entities to enrich query interpretation.
[src:zero-shot-learning/semantic-search] Models like BERT and Sentence-BERT convert words or sentences into dense vectors for similarity comparison.
[src:zero-shot-learning/semantic-search] Semantic ontologies like Web Ontology Language, Resource Description Framework, and Schema.org organize concepts and relationships, allowing systems to infer related terms and deeper meanings.
[src:zero-shot-learning/semantic-search] Hybrid search models combine lexical retrieval (e.g., BM25) with semantic ranking using pretrained transformer models for optimal performance.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] When classification is performed by a computer, statistical methods are normally used to develop the algorithm.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Often, the individual observations are analyzed into a set of quantifiable properties, known variously as explanatory variables or *features*.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] These properties may variously be categorical (e.g.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"), integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email) or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Other classifiers work by comparing observations to previous observations by means of a similarity or distance function.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] An algorithm that implements classification, especially in a concrete implementation, is known as a **classifier**.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] The term "classifier" sometimes also refers to the mathematical function, implemented by a classification algorithm, that maps input data to a category.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Terminology across fields is quite varied.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] In machine learning, the observations are often known as *instances*, the explanatory variables are termed *features* (grouped into a feature vector), and the possible categories to be predicted are *classes*.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Other fields may use different terminology: e.g. in community ecology, the term "classification" normally refers to cluster analysis.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Classification and clustering are examples of the more general problem of pattern recognition, which is the assignment of some sort of output value to a given input value.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] A common subclass of classification is probabilistic classification.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Algorithms of this nature use statistical inference to find the best class for a given instance.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Unlike other algorithms, which simply output a "best" class, probabilistic algorithms output a probability of the instance being a member of each of the possible classes.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] The best class is normally then selected as the one with the highest probability.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Early work on statistical classification was undertaken by Fisher, in the context of two-group problems, leading to Fisher's linear discriminant function as the rule for assigning a group to a new observation.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] This early work assumed that data-values within each of the two groups had a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] The extension of this same context to more than two groups has also been considered with a restriction imposed that the classification rule should be linear.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Unlike frequentist procedures, Bayesian classification procedures provide a natural way of taking into account any available information about the relative sizes of the different groups within the overall population.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Bayesian procedures tend to be computationally expensive and, in the days before Markov chain Monte Carlo computations were developed, approximations for Bayesian clustering rules were devised.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Some Bayesian procedures involve the calculation of group-membership probabilities: these provide a more informative outcome than a simple attribution of a single group-label to each new observation.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Classification can be thought of as two separate problems – binary classification and multiclass classification.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] In binary classification, a better understood task, only two classes are involved, whereas multiclass classification involves assigning an object to one of several classes.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Since many classification methods have been developed specifically for binary classification, multiclass classification often requires the combined use of multiple binary classifiers.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Most algorithms describe an individual instance whose category is to be predicted using a feature vector of individual, measurable properties of the instance.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Each property is termed a feature, also known in statistics as an explanatory variable (or independent variable, although features may or may not be statistically independent).
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] "large", "medium" or "small"); integer-valued (e.g. the number of occurrences of a particular word in an email); or real-valued (e.g. a measurement of blood pressure).
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] If the instance is an image, the feature values might correspond to the pixels of an image; if the instance is a piece of text, the feature values might be occurrence frequencies of different words.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Some algorithms work only in terms of discrete data and require that real-valued or integer-valued data be *discretized* into groups (e.g. less than 5, between 5 and 10, or greater than 10).
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] A large number of algorithms for classification can be phrased in terms of a linear function that assigns a score to each possible category *k* by combining the feature vector of an instance with a vector of weights, using a dot product.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] The predicted category is the one with the highest score.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] In discrete choice theory, where instances represent people and categories represent choices, the score is considered the utility associated with person *i* choosing category *k*.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Algorithms with this basic setup are known as linear classifiers.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] What distinguishes them is the procedure for determining (training) the optimal weights/coefficients and the way that the score is interpreted.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Since no single form of classification is appropriate for all data sets, a large toolkit of classification algorithms has been developed.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] Choices between different possible algorithms are frequently made on the basis of quantitative evaluation of accuracy.
[src:zero-shot-learning/statistical-classification] In some of these, it is employed as a data mining procedure, while in others more detailed statistical modeling is undertaken.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Since transfer learning makes use of training with multiple objective functions it is related to cost-sensitive machine learning and multi-objective optimization.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] In 1976, Bozinovski and Fulgosi published a paper addressing transfer learning in neural network training.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] The paper gives a mathematical and geometrical model of the topic.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] In 1981, a report considered the application of transfer learning to a dataset of images representing letters of computer terminals, experimentally demonstrating positive and negative transfer learning.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] In 1992, Lorien Pratt formulated the discriminability-based transfer (DBT) algorithm.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] By 1998, the field had advanced to include multi-task learning, along with more formal theoretical foundations.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Influential publications on transfer learning include the book *Learning to Learn* in 1998, a 2009 survey and a 2019 survey.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Ng said in his NIPS 2016 tutorial that TL would become the next driver of machine learning commercial success after supervised learning.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] In the 2020 paper, "Rethinking Pre-Training and self-training", Zoph et al. reported that pre-training can hurt accuracy, and advocate self-training instead.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] The definition of transfer learning is given in terms of domains and tasks.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] A domain ${\mathcal {D}}$ consists of: a feature space ${\mathcal {X}}$ and a marginal probability distribution $P(X)$ , where $X=\{x_{1},...,x_{n}\}\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Given a specific domain, ${\mathcal {D}}=\{{\mathcal {X}},P(X)\}$ , a task consists of two components: a label space ${\mathcal {Y}}$ and an objective predictive function $f:{\mathcal {X}}\rightarrow {\mathcal {Y}}$ .
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] The function f is used to predict the corresponding label $f(x)$ of a new instance x .
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Algorithms for transfer learning are available in Markov logic networks and Bayesian networks.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Transfer learning has been applied to cancer subtype discovery, building utilization, general game playing, text classification, digit recognition, medical imaging and spam filtering.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] It was noted that this relationship worked in both directions, showing that EEG brainwaves can likewise be used to classify EMG signals.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] The experiments noted that the accuracy of neural networks and convolutional neural networks were improved through transfer learning both prior to any learning (compared to standard random weight distribution) and at the end of the learning process (asymptote).
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] That is, results are improved by exposure to another domain.
[src:zero-shot-learning/transfer-learning] Moreover, the end-user of a pre-trained model can change the structure of fully-connected layers to improve performance.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] In natural language processing, a **word embedding** is a representation of a word.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Typically, the representation is a real-valued vector that encodes the meaning of the word in such a way that the words that are closer in the vector space are expected to be similar in meaning.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings can be obtained using language modeling and feature learning techniques, where words or phrases from the vocabulary are mapped to vectors of real numbers.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Methods to generate this mapping include neural networks, dimensionality reduction on the word co-occurrence matrix, probabilistic models, explainable knowledge base method, and explicit representation in terms of the context in which words appear.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Word and phrase embeddings, when used as the underlying input representation, have been shown to boost the performance in NLP tasks such as syntactic parsing and sentiment analysis.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] In distributional semantics, a quantitative methodological approach for understanding meaning in observed language, word embeddings or semantic feature space models have been used as a knowledge representation for some time.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Such models aim to quantify and categorize semantic similarities between linguistic items based on their distributional properties in large samples of language data.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The underlying idea that "a word is characterized by the company it keeps" was proposed in a 1957 article by John Rupert Firth, but also has roots in the contemporaneous work on search systems and in cognitive psychology.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The first generation of semantic space models is the vector space model for information retrieval.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Such vector space models for words and their distributional data implemented in their simplest form results in a very sparse vector space of high dimensionality (cf. curse of dimensionality).
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Reducing the number of dimensions using linear algebraic methods such as singular value decomposition then led to the introduction of latent semantic analysis in the late 1980s and the random indexing approach for collecting word co-occurrence contexts.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] In 2000, Bengio et al. provided in a series of papers titled "Neural probabilistic language models" to reduce the high dimensionality of word representations in contexts by "learning a distributed representation for words".
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] A study published in NeurIPS (NIPS) 2002 introduced the use of both word and document embeddings applying the method of kernel CCA to bilingual (and multi-lingual) corpora, also providing an early example of self-supervised learning of word embeddings.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings come in two different styles, one in which words are expressed as vectors of co-occurring words, and another in which words are expressed as vectors of linguistic contexts in which the words occur; these different styles are studied in Lavelli et al., 2004.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Roweis and Saul published in *Science* how to use "locally linear embedding" (LLE) to discover representations of high dimensional data structures.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Most new word embedding techniques after about 2005 rely on a neural network architecture instead of more probabilistic and algebraic models, after foundational work done by Yoshua Bengio and colleagues.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The approach has been adopted by many research groups after theoretical advances in 2010 had been made on the quality of vectors and the training speed of the model, as well as after hardware advances allowed for a broader parameter space to be explored profitably.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] In 2013, a team at Google led by Tomas Mikolov created word2vec, a word embedding toolkit that can train vector space models faster than previous approaches.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The word2vec approach has been widely used in experimentation and was instrumental in raising interest for word embeddings as a technology, moving the research strand out of specialised research into broader experimentation and eventually paving the way for practical application.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Historically, one of the main limitations of static word embeddings or word vector space models is that words with multiple meanings are conflated into a single representation (a single vector in the semantic space).
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] In other words, polysemy and homonymy are not handled properly.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] For example, in the sentence "The club I tried yesterday was great!", it is not clear if the term *club* is related to the word sense of a *club sandwich*, *clubhouse*, *golf club*, or any other sense that *club* might have.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The necessity to accommodate multiple meanings per word in different vectors (multi-sense embeddings) is the motivation for several contributions in NLP to split single-sense embeddings into multi-sense ones.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Most approaches that produce multi-sense embeddings can be divided into two main categories for their word sense representation, i.e., unsupervised and knowledge-based.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Based on word2vec skip-gram, Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (MSSG) performs word-sense discrimination and embedding simultaneously, improving its training time, while assuming a specific number of senses for each word.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] In the Non-Parametric Multi-Sense Skip-Gram (NP-MSSG) this number can vary depending on each word.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Once the words are disambiguated, they can be used in a standard word embeddings technique, so multi-sense embeddings are produced.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] MSSA architecture allows the disambiguation and annotation process to be performed recurrently in a self-improving manner.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The use of multi-sense embeddings is known to improve performance in several NLP tasks, such as part-of-speech tagging, semantic relation identification, semantic relatedness, named entity recognition and sentiment analysis.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] As of the late 2010s, contextually-meaningful embeddings such as ELMo and BERT have been developed.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Unlike static word embeddings, these embeddings are at the token-level, in that each occurrence of a word has its own embedding.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] These embeddings better reflect the multi-sense nature of words, because occurrences of a word in similar contexts are situated in similar regions of BERT's embedding space.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings for *n-*grams in biological sequences (e.g.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] DNA, RNA, and proteins) for bioinformatics applications have been proposed by Asgari and Mofrad.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Named bio-vectors (BioVec) to refer to biological sequences in general with protein-vectors (ProtVec) for proteins (amino-acid sequences) and gene-vectors (GeneVec) for gene sequences, this representation can be widely used in applications of deep learning in proteomics and genomics.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The results presented by Asgari and Mofrad suggest that BioVectors can characterize biological sequences in terms of biochemical and biophysical interpretations of the underlying patterns.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings with applications in game design have been proposed by Rabii and Cook as a way to discover emergent gameplay using logs of gameplay data.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The process requires transcribing actions that occur during a game within a formal language and then using the resulting text to create word embeddings.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The results presented by Rabii and Cook suggest that the resulting vectors can capture expert knowledge about games like chess that are not explicitly stated in the game's rules.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] The idea has been extended to embeddings of entire sentences or even documents, e.g. in the form of the thought vectors concept.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] In 2015, some researchers suggested "skip-thought vectors" as a means to improve the quality of machine translation.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] A more recent and popular approach for representing sentences is Sentence-BERT, or SentenceTransformers, which modifies pre-trained BERT with the use of siamese and triplet network structures.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Software for training and using word embeddings includes Tomáš Mikolov's Word2vec, Stanford University's GloVe, GN-GloVe, Flair embeddings, AllenNLP's ELMo, BERT, fastText, Gensim, Indra, and Deeplearning4j.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Principal Component Analysis (PCA), Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP), and T-Distributed Stochastic Neighbour Embedding (t-SNE) are used to reduce the dimensionality of word vector spaces and visualize word embeddings and clusters.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] For instance, the fastText is also used to calculate word embeddings for text corpora in Sketch Engine that are available online.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Word embeddings may contain the biases and stereotypes contained in the trained dataset, as Bolukbasi et al. points out in the 2016 paper "Man is to Computer Programmer as Woman is to Homemaker?
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] For example, one of the analogies generated using the aforementioned word embedding is "man is to computer programmer as woman is to homemaker".
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Research done by Jieyu Zhao et al. shows that the applications of these trained word embeddings without careful oversight likely perpetuates existing bias in society, which is introduced through unaltered training data.
[src:zero-shot-learning/word-embedding] Furthermore, word embeddings can even amplify these biases.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] Zero-shot methods generally work by associating observed and non-observed classes through auxiliary information that encodes observable distinguishing properties of objects.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] This problem is widely studied in computer vision, natural language processing, and machine perception.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] The first paper on zero-shot learning in natural language processing appeared in a 2008 paper by Chang, Ratinov, Roth, and Srikumar, at the AAAI'08, but the name given to the learning paradigm there was *dataless classification*.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] The first paper on zero-shot learning in computer vision appeared at the same conference, under the name *zero-data learning*.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] The term *zero-shot learning* itself first appeared in the literature in a 2009 paper from Palatucci, Hinton, Pomerleau, and Mitchell at NIPS'09.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] This terminology was repeated later in another computer vision paper and the term *zero-shot learning* caught on, as a take-off on *one-shot learning* that was introduced in computer vision years earlier.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] In computer vision, zero-shot learning models learned parameters for seen classes along with their class representations and rely on representational similarity among class labels so that, during inference, instances can be classified into new classes.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] In natural language processing, the key technical direction developed builds on the ability to "understand the labels"—represent the labels in the same semantic space as that of the documents to be classified.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] This supports the classification of a *single example* without observing any annotated data, the purest form of zero-shot classification.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] The original paper made use of the Explicit Semantic Analysis (ESA) representation but later papers made use of other representations, including dense representations.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] This approach was also extended to multilingual domains, fine entity typing and other problems.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] Moreover, beyond relying solely on representations, the computational approach has been extended to depend on transfer from other tasks, such as textual entailment and question answering.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] The original paper also points out that, beyond the ability to classify a single example, when a collection of examples is given, with the assumption that they come from the same distribution, it is possible to bootstrap the performance in a semi-supervised like manner (or transductive learning).
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] Unlike standard generalization in machine learning, where classifiers are expected to correctly classify new samples to classes they have already observed during training, in ZSL, no samples from the classes have been given during training the classifier.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] It can therefore be viewed as an extreme case of domain adaptation.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] Naturally, some form of auxiliary information has to be given about these zero-shot classes, and this type of information can be of several types.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] The above ZSL setup assumes that at test time, only zero-shot samples are given, namely, samples from new unseen classes.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] In generalized zero-shot learning, samples from both new and known classes may appear at test time.
[src:zero-shot-learning/zero-shot-learning] This poses new challenges for classifiers at test time, because it is very challenging to estimate if a given sample is new or known.
